               <floruit>455<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e20612"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e20577" n="66"> On the interchange of
                                    <span xml:lang="gr"></span> with <span xml:lang="gr"></span> in Greek orthography see vol.
                                1, Introduction 2.3.3.2, p. 22. On the unusual declension see vol.
                                3, Introduction 2.8.5, p.
                        21.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e20602" n="67"> The inscription is accompanied by a cross,
                                obviously signifying Christianity. Di Segni, ibid., suggests, based on his sons’ names, that their
                                father may have been a Jew or Samaritan, who converted to keep his
                                job, but see vol. 3, Introduction 6.6.7, p. 52.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e20612" n="68"> The inscription is dated according to the era
                                of Gadara, see Introduction 7.5.4.3.</note>
            </person>
